# Contributing to VOID STRIKER

Thanks for taking an interest in improving VOID STRIKER! This is a single-file
browser game — contributions are welcome whether you're fixing a typo, tuning
game-feel numbers, or adding a whole new feature.

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Getting started](#getting-started)
2. [Project structure](#project-structure)
3. [How to contribute](#how-to-contribute)
4. [Code style](#code-style)
5. [Adding features](#adding-features)
6. [Reporting bugs](#reporting-bugs)
7. [Pull request checklist](#pull-request-checklist)

---

## Getting started

No build step required. Clone the repo and open `index.html` in a browser:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-org/void-striker.git
cd void-striker
# Open index.html in any modern browser, or use a local server:
npx serve .
```

> **Tip:** Use a local server (e.g. `npx serve`, VS Code Live Server, or
> Python's `python3 -m http.server`) so that `fetch()` calls for audio assets
> work correctly.

---

## Project structure

```
void-striker/
├── index.html        ← entire game (HTML + inline CSS + inline JS)
├── audio.js          ← Web Audio sound engine
├── boss.js           ← boss enemy system
├── shop.js           ← between-wave upgrade shop
├── stats.js          ← session & all-time statistics
├── assets/
│   ├── logo.png
│   ├── favicon.ico
│   ├── gameplay.gif
│   ├── screenshots/
│   └── sounds/
│       ├── laser.wav
│       ├── explosion.wav
│       ├── powerup.wav
│       └── boss.wav
├── LICENSE
├── CHANGELOG.md
└── CONTRIBUTING.md   ← you are here
```

The game is intentionally zero-dependency. Please do not introduce npm
packages, bundlers, or framework code. Vanilla JS only.

---

## How to contribute

1. **Fork** the repository and create a branch from `main`:

   ```bash
   git checkout -b fix/spread-shot-clip
   # or
   git checkout -b feat/shield-recharge-animation
   ```

2. Make your changes. Keep commits focused — one logical change per commit.

3. Test in at least two browsers (Chrome + Firefox recommended).

4. Open a **pull request** against `main` and fill in the PR template.

---

## Code style

- **No build tools.** All JavaScript is plain ES5/ES6 — no TypeScript, no JSX.
- **IIFE modules.** Each module (`Boss`, `Shop`, `Stats`, `Audio`) is wrapped
  in an IIFE returning a public API object. Follow the same pattern.
- **`'use strict';`** at the top of every JS file.
- **Constants in SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE**, private variables prefixed with `_`.
- **Tabs for indentation** (2-space visual width) to match the existing file.
- Comments above non-obvious logic; JSDoc on every public function.
- No `console.log` left in submitted code (use `console.warn` for
  recoverable errors that a user might want to see in devtools).

### Naming conventions

| Thing          | Convention              | Example               |
|----------------|-------------------------|-----------------------|
| Module objects | PascalCase IIFE         | `const Boss = (() => …)()` |
| Private vars   | `_camelCase`            | `let _boss = null`    |
| Public methods | `camelCase`             | `Boss.checkBulletHit` |
| Constants      | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`  | `const MAX_LIVES = 3` |
| DOM ids        | `kebab-case`            | `id="shop-close-btn"` |

---

## Adding features

### New enemy type

1. Add the type string to the `type` field in `spawnWave()` in `index.html`.
2. Add draw logic to `drawEnemy(ctx, e)`.
3. Set appropriate `hp`, `shootTimer`, and scoring values.
4. Document the new type in `CHANGELOG.md` under `[Unreleased]`.

### New power-up

1. Add an entry to `Powerups.TYPES` in `index.html`:
   - `icon`, `color`, `glowColor`, `label`, `desc`, `duration`
   - `apply(state)` — immediate effect
   - `expire(state)` — cleanup when timer runs out (omit for instant effects)
2. Test that `expire()` fully reverses `apply()`.

### New achievement

1. Add a descriptor to `Achievements.DEFS` in `index.html`:
   - `id`, `icon`, `name`, `desc`, `check(session) → boolean`
2. Ensure the session stat you rely on is incremented in the right callback
   (`onKill`, `onHit`, `onWaveClear`, etc.).
3. Add a unit-testable condition — keep `check()` pure.

### New upgrade (shop)

1. Add an entry to `Shop.CATALOGUE` in `shop.js`.
2. Implement `effect(level)` returning a state-patch object.
3. If the upgrade has a wave-start side-effect (like extra lives), handle it
   in `applyWaveStartBonuses()`.

### Audio

1. Add the sound file to `assets/sounds/` (44 100 Hz mono WAV recommended).
2. Register the filename in `Audio.FILES` in `audio.js`.
3. Add a convenience method (e.g. `Audio.newSound()`).

---

## Reporting bugs

Open a GitHub Issue and include:

- **Browser & OS** — e.g. Chrome 124 on macOS 14
- **Steps to reproduce** — be specific (wave number, power-ups active, etc.)
- **Expected behaviour** vs **actual behaviour**
- A screenshot or screen recording if possible

Bug reports for mobile are especially appreciated — touch handling is tricky.

---

## Pull request checklist

Before opening a PR, confirm:

- [ ] Tested in Chrome and Firefox
- [ ] No `console.log` left in the code
- [ ] Public functions have JSDoc comments
- [ ] `CHANGELOG.md` updated under `[Unreleased]`
- [ ] PR title follows format: `fix: short description` or `feat: short description`
- [ ] No new external dependencies introduced

---

## Code of conduct

Be kind. Critique ideas, not people. We're all here because we enjoy making
things. Low-effort disparagement of anyone's contribution will result in
removal from the project.

---

*Thanks again — every bug fix, balancing tweak, and new feature makes the
void a little more fun to strike.*

